Interview Questions
Q1. What is a Deque in Java and what does it stand for?
-->What is Deque?
      
      Deque stands for Double Ended Queue.
      
      It is an interface that extends the Queue interface and allows insertion and deletion of elements from both the front and the rear.
      
      It can behave as both:
      
      Queue (FIFO)
      Stack (LIFO)
      
      Common implementations:
      
      ArrayDeque
      LinkedList
      
      Example:
      
      import java.util.*;
      
      public class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
      
              Deque<Integer> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
      
              deque.addFirst(10);
              deque.addLast(20);
      
              System.out.println(deque);
          }
      }
      
      Output
      
      [10, 20]






Q2. How is Deque different from a Queue?
-->
| Queue                        | Deque                          |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Insertion/removal at one end | Insertion/removal at both ends |
| Follows FIFO                 | Supports FIFO and LIFO         |
| Less flexible                | More flexible                  |
| Single-ended                 | Double-ended                   |






Q3. What type of data structure behavior does Deque support?
-->Deque supports both:

    1. FIFO (First In, First Out)
          Front → 10 20 30 ← Rear
    2. LIFO (Last In, First Out)
          Top
          30
          20
          10
          
        Thus, a Deque can work as either a Queue or a Stack.




Q4. Can Deque be used as both a Stack and a Queue?
-->Yes.
    
    As a Queue (FIFO)
    Deque<Integer> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
    
    deque.offer(10);
    deque.offer(20);
    
    System.out.println(deque.poll());
    
    Output :
      10

    
    As a Stack (LIFO)
        Deque<Integer> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
        
        deque.push(10);
        deque.push(20);
        
        System.out.println(deque.pop());
        
        Output
        
        20





Q5. Does Deque allow duplicate elements?
-->Yes.
    
    Deque allows duplicate elements.
    
    Example:
    
    Deque<String> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
    
    deque.add("Java");
    deque.add("Java");
    
    System.out.println(deque);
    
    Output
    
    [Java, Java]





Q6. Does Deque allow null values? If not, why?
-->No.
      
      Most Deque implementations, such as ArrayDeque, do not allow null values.
      
      Reason
      
      Methods like poll(), peek(), and remove() use null to indicate that the deque is empty. Allowing null elements would create ambiguity.
      
      Example:
      
      Deque<String> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
      
      deque.add(null);
      
      Output
      
      Exception in thread "main"
      java.lang.NullPointerException
      Interview Tip
      PriorityQueue → Orders elements by priority, internally uses a Binary Heap (Min-Heap), allows duplicates, does not allow null.
      Deque → Stands for Double Ended Queue, supports both FIFO and LIFO, implemented by ArrayDeque and LinkedList, and generally does not
      allow null values.




      
